export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p><em>A meta-review of AI and ab initio simulation errors in nine classes of high-value hard materials, and the discovery roadmap they imply — an independent-researcher position paper from Lupine Science.</em></p>\n<p>Research date: 2026-07-17; every program status, deadline, and price is stated as of that date. Throughout, MAE means mean absolute error; magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy is spelled out where it appears.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "1-1-1", "html": "<p>My thesis has three parts. First, simulation error — not data, interest, or capital — is the binding constraint on discovery in the most strategically valuable hard materials: the classes Beijing and Washington name first in their priority instruments are precisely the ones modern simulation handles worst. Second, machine-learned interatomic potentials (MLIPs) trained on density-functional-theory (DFT) labels inherit DFT's systematic floors, so a bigger model on the same labels asymptotes instead of improving; the floor breaks only under fidelity escalation — non-equilibrium data, multi-fidelity labels, experiment-anchored correction — not under scale. Third, because the demonstrated fixes are cheap, public, and unowned, a rare three-to-five-year level playing field is open, and an independent, validation-first venture can lead it. I run that venture solo and treat the scale as an asset: no foundation model to defend, nothing to stop me publishing an uncertainty interval beside every prediction.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "1-2-1", "html": "<p>Five flagship error numbers carry the first thesis point. Across 574 DFT-NEB migration paths, the five most-used universal MLIPs miss lithium-ion migration barriers by 0.310–0.349 eV MAE against a ~60 meV DFT-NEB floor — and since 60 meV of barrier error changes diffusivity tenfold at 298 K, a screening funnel built on them misjudges ionic transport by up to five orders of magnitude.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup> Open Catalyst 2020's own builders report that ML energy errors plateaued near 0.2 eV for about two years, against a 0.1 eV target set by the estimated error of the underlying DFT itself.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup> On the MS25 benchmark's hardest case — a five-element alloy with a classical-potential ground truth, so no label noise to blame — five architectures miss the 2.5 meV/atom usability threshold four- to fivefold.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> One benchmark suite finds the GRACE-2L foundation potential 617.9 meV/atom off zero-shot on the 25-element HEA25S alloy.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup> And one industry synthesis puts reduced-activation ferritic/martensitic (RAFM) steel validation near 20 displacements per atom (dpa) against a 50-dpa DEMO blanket requirement; the design figures beneath are EUROfusion's own.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"7\">[7]</sup></p>\n<p><strong>Table 1.1 — The report in nine numbers.</strong> One headline quantified error per admitted class; markers preserve each source's index in its originating corpus file (disambiguated in the companion citemap); chain numbers follow Chapter 15.</p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Class</th>\n<th>Headline quantified error</th>\n<th>Corpus source</th>\n<th>Chain anchored</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Superconductors (Ch. 4)</td>\n<td>Harmonic electron–phonon <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span> 2.64 vs 1.84 anharmonic on H<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>S — ~43% high; no ab initio <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> exists for unconventional families</td>\n<td>dim01 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"8\">[8]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"9\">[9]</sup></td>\n<td>8</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Correlated oxides &amp; quantum (Ch. 5)</td>\n<td>Semilocal DFT returns NiO and CoO as metals; HSE and diffusion Monte Carlo split ~1 eV on ZnO's oxygen vacancy</td>\n<td>dim02 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"10\">[10]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"11\">[11]</sup></td>\n<td>9</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>High-entropy alloys &amp; disorder (Ch. 6)</td>\n<td>Five architectures 4–5× the 2.5 meV/atom threshold on MS25's five-element alloy; one benchmark suite finds 617.9 meV/atom zero-shot</td>\n<td>dim03 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup></td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Batteries (Ch. 7)</td>\n<td>Migration-barrier MAE 0.310–0.349 eV across 574 DFT-NEB paths vs ~60 meV floor; 73–78% of barriers underestimated</td>\n<td>dim04 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup></td>\n<td>1</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Catalysts (Ch. 8)</td>\n<td>GGA adsorption mean errors 0.2–0.4 eV vs experiment; OC20 ML energy MAE plateaued ~0.2 eV for ~2 years</td>\n<td>dim05 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"12\">[12]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup></td>\n<td>3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Magnets &amp; REE-free (Ch. 9)</td>\n<td>Curie-temperature errors 15–35% with non-systematic sign (Fe<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B +35%, Co<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>B ×1.5 low); micromagnetic coercivity ~5× high</td>\n<td>dim06 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"13\">[13]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"14\">[14]</sup></td>\n<td>2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Fusion &amp; nuclear (Ch. 10)</td>\n<td>Best cascade MLIP spans 240 ps vs a five-year service life; RAFM validated ~20 of the 50 dpa required</td>\n<td>dim07 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"15\">[15]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"7\">[7]</sup></td>\n<td>7</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Porous frameworks &amp; 2D (Ch. 11)</td>\n<td>Semi-empirical van der Waals corrections 0.77–3.04× the RPA interlayer energy (one benchmark suite); cross-zeolite transfer inflates energy error ≥10×</td>\n<td>dim08 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"16\">[16]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup></td>\n<td>5</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>WBG semiconductors · perovskites · thermoelectrics (Ch. 12)</td>\n<td>LDA gap underestimate ~50% across a 472-material benchmark; ~1 eV error cancellation inside Pb-halide perovskite gaps</td>\n<td>dim09 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"18\">[18]</sup></td>\n<td>6, 11</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Three features of the error column matter more than any row. The errors are largest where strategic value is certified: every row sits inside a national priority instrument, and the hardest documented case in the field's observable-first suite — a five-element alloy defeating five architectures — is a class both governments name in writing. The errors are systematic, not random: barriers are underestimated one-directionally, ground states fail qualitatively, Curie-temperature errors flip sign between neighboring borides — so no funnel averages them out. And every row carries at least one demonstrated correction lever with a published before-and-after number, which makes the table a work order rather than a lament. Chapters 4–12 carry the full case loads; the chain column is where each measured error converts into a falsifiable commitment.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "1-2-2", "html": "<p>The demonstrated fixes are the report's second evidentiary leg. Non-equilibrium pretraining on OMat24 cuts out-of-distribution cleavage-energy error from a 14.7% median absolute percentage error to 2.9% at identical architecture — a 5× data effect, 17× for EquiformerV2.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"19\">[19]</sup> One study finds that training on 90% GGA plus 10% SCAN labels matches a model trained on eight times as much pure SCAN data — high fidelity at roughly a tenth of the expensive labels.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup> And fine-tuning with a single added DFT structure halves the systematic potential-energy-surface softening of universal MLIPs; about 100 frames restore DFT-level spectra.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup> All three are dataset interventions executable in GPU-days by one researcher — the cost structure on which the entire program rests.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "1-3-1", "html": "<p>Eleven discovery chains convert the measured errors into commitments, each written in one grammar — <em>because we have unlocked a named error-correction capability, we will discover X, build Y, and impact people in Z ways</em> — and each carrying a measured current-versus-solved pair. The two flagship chains, unabridged:</p>\n<p><em>Because we have unlocked barrier-accurate machine-learned interatomic potentials, we will discover solid electrolytes and cathode coatings with verified ionic transport, with verified-transport electrolytes we will be able to build 500 Wh/kg-class solid-state batteries. This impacts people in three ways to improve their world: cheaper, mineral-secure electric vehicles for drivers; affordable power for grid customers when the wind drops; first electricity, delivered as storage, for off-grid communities.</em></p>\n<p><em>Because we have unlocked spin-aware, multi-fidelity magnetic simulation, we will discover NdFeB-class rare-earth-free magnets — Fe<span class=\"math\">$_{16}$</span>N<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>, MnAlC, kinetically unlocked tetrataenite — with such magnets we will be able to build motors and turbines immune to export controls. This impacts people in three ways to improve their world: drivers and factory towns whose EVs and wind power stop pricing in a chokepoint; planners who quit scheduling around a foreign licensing decision; magnet workers competing on physics instead of quotas.</em></p>\n<p>Chain 1's gap is 0.310–0.349 eV against a ≤40 meV solved target (≈1 kcal/mol); chain 2's is sign-unstable 15–35% Curie-temperature error against ranking-faithful prediction. Chapter 15 writes all eleven; Chapter 18 phases them against dated gates. No chain names a discovery date.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "1-3-2", "html": "<p>The demand side is dual. China's 15th Five-Year Plan names fifteen material classes verbatim across three funding postures — breakthrough, upgrade, frontier — thirteen mapping onto this report's nine classes, and pairs the list with a ¥1tn national venture-capital guidance fund for early, small, long-term, hard-technology investment.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"23\">[23]</sup> The United States answers with the USGS 60-mineral critical list,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"24\">[24]</sup> the Genesis Mission's $293M AI-for-science funding announcement,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"25\">[25]</sup> and the small-business programs reauthorized under P.L. 119-83, whose first NSF full-proposal deadline falls on 2026-07-27.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"26\">[26]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup> Both systems pay for outcomes in the same nine classes; neither funds the error audit its own priorities are gated on. That unowned layer is the venture's address.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "1-4-1", "html": "<p>This field has earned its trust deficit, and I write under it. Berkeley's A-Lab required a Nature Author Correction — dated 2026-01-19 in secondary accounts, issue-dated February 2026 by the journal — that walked back the novelty claims;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"28\">[28]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"29\">[29]</sup> Cheetham and Seshadri argued that few of GNoME's 381,000 &quot;newly discovered stable materials&quot; survive a novelty–credibility–utility trifecta, their characterization rather than a census;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"30\">[30]</sup> and the field's most-cited productivity statistic, &quot;44% more materials,&quot; was fabricated and disowned by MIT.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"31\">[31]</sup> Three falsifiers bind this report: the inherited floor falls if a model trained on PBE-class labels matches experiment on chemically held-out sets; the level playing field falls the day any player closes a discovery-to-qualified-part loop in one of the nine classes; the validation-first wedge falls if database-scale predictions convert into independently audited novel materials faster than small prospective funnels. My answer is procedural, and I hold myself to it first: every quantitative claim here carries a source, a date, and a confidence flag, single-source items are hedged inline, and any error I make will be corrected the way I ask of the field — dated, public, and mine.</p>\n" },
]
